@article{Bronnikov&Belianin&Upravitelev2023,
  abstract={Loneliness is a significant problem of our times: 
            each second individual feels lonely at least occasionally, 
            and each seventeenth experiences it often or always. 
            The dramatic negative effects of loneliness are known 
            from the literature to be both for mental and physical health. 
            However, loneliness is still an under-researched area. 
            Specifically, there is no study on the social and 
            economic preferences that establishes the causal effect of loneliness. 
            To the best of our knowledge, our paper is the first 
            that deals with this using economic laboratory settings. 
            We document the multidimensional effect of loneliness on 
            social and economic preferences. The major implication of our 
            studies provides the reasons why and through which mechanism 
            lonely individuals can be much easier exploited than non (or less) 
            lonely ones and, hence, at higher risk. Our paper also provides 
            insights for policymakers on how to mitigate it.},
